<TITLE> Stocks end upbeat on banks </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Dec 13 (bdnews24.com)--Stocks ended upbeat Thursday after falling in the previous four days with banks dominating the turnover board. "It was a totally bank-led recovery on Thursday. There were some very visible signs of market recovery, such as increased turnover on the bourse, wider difference of gainers beating losers," market analyst Yaweer Sayeed, also managing director of AIMS of Bangladesh, told bdnews24.com. "At the end of the day, it seems that the market has started to run in a standard manner," he said. The Dhaka Stock Exchange on the last trading day of the week opened with a steep rise in the general index before declining a bit in the second hour of trading. It however recovered losses in the midday session and remained more or less stable towards the end. The DGEN or general index closed at 2936.16, up 37.82 points or 1.3 percent. The DSI or all share price index rose 28.49 points or 1.16 percent to 2474.91. The DSE-20 blue chip index also edged up 31.48 points, or 1.36 percent, to close at 2342. Turnover increased to Tk 1.08 billion from Wednesday's Tk 1.1 billion from trading of 4,939,626 shares. Gainers beat losers 154 to 40 and 24 issues remained unchanged. BRAC Bank was at the peak of the top share board by value. It closed 1.39 percent higher at Tk 1567.25. UCBL dipped 0.65 percent to Tk 4473.75. NBL continued to gain, closing at Tk 1377.25, up 3.51 percent. The Bank, in response to a DSE query, said that there had been no undisclosed price sensitive information for the recent unusual price hike. Newer entrant, Islami Bank Perpetual Bond closed steady after falling the previous day. It ended at Tk 1436.25. South East Bank increased 2.60 percent to Tk 560.50. Among the other scrips on the top share board by valueShahjalal Bank, Keya Cosmetics and Square Pharma gained. Dutch Bangla Bank and Power Grid Company of Bangladesh, however, declined. Keya Detergent, Gulf Foods, Wonderland Toys, Monospool Paper and Apex Weaving were among the major gainers. Purabi General Insurance, Dutch Bangla Bank, ICB Dynamic Textile and Bangladesh Thai Aluminum topped the losers. All the indices on the Chittagong Stock Exchange also ended higher. The CSCX or selective categories index closed 49.24 points or 1.04 percent up at 4782.92. The CASPI or all share price index ended at 7467.94, up 65.51 points or 0.88 percent. The CSE-30 blue chip also rose to 6595.23, up 79.71 points or 1.22 percent. Turnover on the port city's bourse rose to Tk 181.403 million from Tk 145.063 million. Of the issues traded on the CSE, 81 advanced, 28 declined and 8 held steady. bdn
